  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The eyepiece
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   used by astronomer Edwin Hubble from the Mount Wilson Observatory's 100-inch Hooker Telescope,
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   once the world's most powerful, was carried into orbit by the shuttle
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   that launched the space telescope honoring him, a symbolic gesture from astronomy's past to its future.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Using the Hooker telescope, Hubble was the first
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   to determine the distance to a galaxy outside the Milky Way.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   This provided evidence for the concept
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   that the universe is expanding.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   His work helped convince scientists
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   that the universe was created in a giant explosion,
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   called the "big bang."
  </a>
  <a href="#12" id="12">
   The Hooker Telescope was mothballed in 1985.
  </a>
